Xlang — layered open-source licenses
===================================

Copyright (C) 2026 ShuLiangfu <admin@shuliangfu.com>
Project: https://github.com/shuliangfu/shux
Contact: admin@shuliangfu.com

Xlang uses a **layered licensing** model: the language runtime and standard
library are under a permissive license so end-user programs are not forced
into copyleft; the compiler and toolchain remain under a strong copyleft
license (with optional commercial terms).

This file is the **primary license map**. Full legal texts:

  - AGPL-3.0:     [LICENSE.AGPL-3.0](LICENSE.AGPL-3.0)
  - Apache-2.0:   [LICENSE.Apache-2.0](LICENSE.Apache-2.0)

Third-party components, path-level exceptions, and recommended source
headers: [NOTICE](NOTICE).

================================================================================
1. Layer A — Compiler / toolchain (AGPL-3.0-or-later)
================================================================================

Unless a more specific notice applies, the following are licensed under the
**GNU Affero General Public License version 3 or later** (AGPL-3.0-or-later):

  - compiler/          (frontend, backend, driver, seeds product logic, …)
  - tools/             (repo maintenance / migration tooling)
  - build.x, build_runner.x, build_runtime.x, build_runtime_x.x, build.sh
  - mind/, analysis/   (project engineering docs; still AGPL unless marked)
  - Other repository paths **not** listed under Layer B or an exception below

Full text: LICENSE.AGPL-3.0

SPDX for Layer A sources:

  SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later

Commercial licensing (AGPL copyleft exemption for proprietary embedding of
the **compiler/toolchain**, closed distribution of modified toolchain, or
modified network services without offering corresponding source) is available
from the copyright holder:

  ShuLiangfu <admin@shuliangfu.com>

Commercial terms are offered only for code the copyright holder owns or has
rights to relicense. They do **not** replace third-party licenses (see NOTICE).

================================================================================
2. Layer B — Language core & standard library (Apache-2.0)
================================================================================

The following are licensed under the **Apache License, Version 2.0**:

  - core/              (language core library)
  - std/               (standard library)

Full text: LICENSE.Apache-2.0

SPDX for Layer B sources:

  SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0

Intent: programs you write in Xlang that link or depend on core/std may be
distributed under terms you choose for **your** code, subject only to Apache-2.0
obligations for any Apache-licensed portions you redistribute (copyright
notices, NOTICE retention where applicable, etc.). Using the Xlang **compiler**
to build your program does not, by itself, place your program under AGPL.

================================================================================
3. Layer C — Editor integrations (permissive)
================================================================================

  - editors/vscode/            Apache-2.0  (see editors/vscode/LICENSE)
  - editors/tree-sitter-xlang/  Apache-2.0  (see that directory)
  - editors/vim/               Apache-2.0  (same default as language surface
                                           unless a file says otherwise)

================================================================================
4. Examples, tests, and user-facing samples
================================================================================

  - examples/   Apache-2.0  (default; free to copy into your projects)
  - tests/      Apache-2.0  (default; harnesses and fixtures)

Compiler-internal fixtures that live **under** compiler/ remain Layer A (AGPL).

================================================================================
5. Generated code and end-user programs
================================================================================

  - Copyright in **your** source programs remains yours.
  - Object code / binaries you produce from **your** sources are yours to
    license, except you must comply with licenses of any libraries you link
    (including Apache-2.0 core/std if redistributed, and any system libraries).
  - The AGPL applies to the Xlang **compiler/toolchain** as a program (and to
    modified versions you convey), not automatically to every program merely
    compiled with an unmodified Xlang toolchain.

This section is a project policy statement; it does not amend the AGPL or
Apache license texts themselves.

================================================================================
6. How to choose (practical)
================================================================================

  - Writing apps / libraries in Xlang, shipping products that use core/std
      → Layer B (Apache-2.0). Keep notices when you redistribute those parts.

  - Modifying, embedding, or redistributing the Xlang **compiler** / toolchain
      → Layer A (AGPL-3.0-or-later), or contact us for commercial terms.

  - VS Code / Cursor extension
      → Apache-2.0 (editors/vscode).

================================================================================
7. SPDX summary
================================================================================

  AGPL-3.0-or-later    Layer A (compiler / toolchain / default for unlisted)
  Apache-2.0           Layer B (core, std), examples, tests, tree-sitter, vim, vscode
  Zlib                 vendored orlp ed25519 (see NOTICE)

================================================================================
End of license map — full legal texts in LICENSE.AGPL-3.0 and LICENSE.Apache-2.0
